The Jacob H. Schiff School, a cornerstone of the Harlem community where we are dedicated to nurturing the infinite potential of every student. Founded in 1952 on the grounds of the Hebrew Orphan Asylum, our school carries forward the legacy of our namesake, Jacob H. Schiff, a philanthropist committed to civil rights and educational equity. Guided by our core values of Justice, Honor, and Self-discipline, we provide a safe and supportive environment that encourages intellectual curiosity, critical thinking, and personal growth. Our mission is to ensure that every child is respected, challenged, and empowered to become a lifelong learner and an active, compassionate member of society.

At P.S. 192, we believe in the boundless possibilities of each student. Our vision is to foster independent thinkers who are prepared to make a positive impact in their communities. Through our school’s motto—“Good, better, best. Never let it rest until your good is better, and your better is best”—we inspire students to strive for excellence in all they do. As a community of joyful learning, we are committed to unlocking each student’s full potential, instilling a love for learning, and shaping future leaders. Thank you for your continued support of our school and its mission.

With justice, honor, and self-discipline,
Hilduara Abreu
Principal, P.S. 192 – The School of Joyful Learning

Our Mission Statement
PS/IS 192, The Magnet School for Math and Science Inquiry is the school of character and intelligence.  At PS/IS 192, each student is special and precious.  Our school mission is to use every minute for every child to excel as a student and as a citizen. 

Instructional Bottom Lines
We will use student work and data to drive focused individualized instruction.  We will maintain a focused implementation of the workshop model in reading, writing, and math.  We will organize our learning environment to support our best teaching practices and student achievement.   We will use investigative methods to encourage inquiry-based learning in Math and Science. 

The Engineering Design Process

When conducting inquiry based learning and working on our STEAM projects, we follow the Engineering Design Process in which we: 
Ask: Students as questions that will help them reach their goal and think about their constraints.
Imagine: Students brainstorm ideas and choose the best one.
Plan: Students sketch their idea and list the materials they will need.
Create: Students create a prototype of their idea and test to see if it works.
Improve: Students reflect on ways to make improvements and make changes to their original idea.
